<DOC><DOCNO> AP891121-0147 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 1943EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-India-Elections-Glance     11-21 0404</FIRST><SECOND>AM-India-Elections-Glance,0418</SECOND><HEAD>Indian Elections at a Glance</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-India, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Facts and figures on India'sparliamentary elections:</TEXT><TEXT>   THE VOTING _ Voting begins Wednesday, when 221 constituencies goto the polls; 266 go to the polls on Friday and 37 on Sunday.</TEXT><TEXT>   THE VOTERS _ There are 498 million registered voters. Thegovernment last year lowered the voting age from 21 to 18, addingabout 35 million people to the electorate.</TEXT><TEXT>   THE SEATS _ The winners of the elections will enter the LokSabha or House of the People, the decision-making lower house ofParliament. The house has 545 members, of whom two are nominated.Elections are not being held for 14 seats in the northeastern stateof Assam because voters' lists have not been completed. But therewill be voting in only 524 constituencies. Elections in fourconstituencies have been postponed because of the deaths ofcandidates; in another constituency, one candidate ran unopposed.</TEXT><TEXT>   THE CANDIDATES _ There are 6,090 candidates, including at least4,000 independents. Candidates are also from eight nationalparties, 33 state parties and 251 other parties. The Congress Partyof Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi is fielding 509 candidates. TheNational Front, an opposition coalition, is up for 314 seats. Inmost constituencies, the front has agreed not to oppose candidatesof the the right-wing Bharatiya Janata Party, which is fielding 226candidates, the Communist Party of India (53 candidates) and theCommunist Party-Marxist (64 candidates.) However, the left partiesand the right-wing group will oppose each other.</TEXT><TEXT>   KEY ISSUES _ The Congress Party, which won an unprecedented 415seats in the last election in 1984, is beset by opposition chargesof corruption. Opinion polls say it may lose its majority. Thegoverning party has campaigned this year on a platform of pastperformances and continuing stability in government.</TEXT><TEXT>   COUNTING _ Counting of votes begins Sunday.</TEXT><TEXT>   PREVIOUS ELECTION _ In 1984, the Congress Party won 415 seats,the right-wing Bharatiya Janata Party 2, the centerist Janata(People's) Party 10, the centerist Lok Kranti Dal (People'sRevolutionary Party) 3, the Communist Party of India 6, theCommunist Party-Marxist 22, the Congress Party-Socialist five,major state parties 59, smaller parties 16 and independents five.In the current election, the Janata Party, the Lok Kranti Dal, theCongress-Socialist and three of the larger state parties haveformed the National Front coalition.</TEXT></DOC>